To resize an image in CSS, you can use the `width` and `height` properties. 

For example: 

```
img {
  width: 50%;
  height: auto;
}
```

This would set the image width to 50% of its parent container and automatically adjust its height proportionately. 

You can also set specific pixel values for the `width` and `height` properties. For example: 

```
img {
  width: 200px;
  height: 150px;
}
```

This would set the image width to 200 pixels and height to 150 pixels. 

It's important to keep in mind that resizing an image using CSS can affect its overall quality and may result in distortion if the proportions are not maintained. Ideally, images should be resized and optimized before being added to a web page.

To make the image stretch when the width of the tab is increased, you can use the CSS property `object-fit` with a value of `cover`. This will make the image fill the entire container and stretch or shrink as needed.

Here is an example code:

```
img {
  width: 100%;
  height: 250px; /*you can set the height to any value that fits your design*/
  object-fit: cover;
}
```

In this example, the `width` is set to 100%, which means the image will always expand to fill the width of the container. The `height` is also set to a specific value, but you can adjust it to fit your design needs. Finally, the `object-fit` property is set to `cover` which will make the image stretch or shrink to fill the container while maintaining its aspect ratio.

If the image is already in a container with `display: inline-block;` applied, you can still use the `object-fit` property to stretch the image when the container is resized. 

Here is an example code:

```
.container {
  display: inline-block;
  max-width: 100%;
  height: 250px; /*you can set the height to any value that fits your design*/
}

.container img {
  width: 100%;
  height: 100%;
  object-fit: cover;
}
```

In this example, the `max-width` property is set to `100%` to allow the container to resize with the width of the tab. The `height` property of the container and image are also set to a specific value, but you can adjust it to fit your design needs.

The `width` and `height` of the image are set to `100%` to match the dimensions of the container. Finally, the `object-fit` property is set to `cover` to make the image stretch or shrink to fill the container while maintaining its aspect ratio.

By using these CSS properties, the image will stretch as the container is resized while maintaining its aspect ratio.

If the image is not stretching out when you increase the tab width, it could be due to the container's `max-width` and `height` properties. 

Try setting the `max-width` and `height` properties to `100%` for both the container and image. This will make sure that the container and image always fill the available width and height of the parent element, which will allow the image to stretch when the tab is wider.

