To give styling to a common class in all HTML but target a specific HTML element, you can use a combination of the class selector and element selector. For example, consider this HTML:

```
<div class="box">Box 1</div>
<div class="box">Box 2</div>
<div class="box">Box 3</div>
```

Let's say you want to apply a specific style to the second box, `Box 2`. You could do this with the following CSS:

```
.box {
  background-color: gray;
  border: 1px solid black;
  padding: 10px;
}

.box:nth-of-type(2) {
  background-color: blue;
  color: white;
}
```

In this example, the first three properties apply to all elements with the class `.box`, including `Box 1`, `Box 2`, and `Box 3`, giving them a gray background, black border, and 10px padding. However, the last two properties in the code block apply only to the second element with the class `.box` (i.e. `Box 2`), using the `:nth-of-type` pseudo-class to target the specific element by its position in the HTML.

Using this approach, you can target specific elements with a common CSS class by using an additional selector that differentiates the elements based on their position or other attributes.

To give CSS styling to an element with an ID of "last", you can use the ID selector in your CSS to apply styling specifically to that element. Here's an example:

HTML:

```
<div id="first">First element</div>
<div id="second">Second element</div>
<div id="last">Last element</div>
```

CSS:

```
#last {
  background-color: yellow;
  color: black;
  font-size: 18px;
  padding: 10px;
}
```

In this example, the `#last` selector targets the element with the ID of "last" and applies a yellow background, black text color, font size of 18 pixels, and 10 pixels of padding on all sides.

Note that IDs are unique to each HTML element, so only one element in the HTML document should have an ID of "last". If you have multiple elements with similar properties that you need to target, it may be more appropriate to use a class instead of an ID.

window.addEventListener("scroll", function() {
    var scrollPosition = window.pageYOffset || document.documentElement.scrollTop || document.body.scrollTop || 0;
    var windowHeight = window.innerHeight || document.documentElement.clientHeight || document.body.clientHeight || 0;
    var bodyHeight = document.documentElement.scrollHeight || document.body.scrollHeight || 0;

    if (scrollPosition + windowHeight >= bodyHeight) {
        document.querySelector("footer").style.display = "block";
    } else {
        document.querySelector("footer").style.display = "none";
    }
});
